content.text: Python Sets

content.code_html: myset = {"apple", "banana", "cherry"}

content.text: Set
Sets are used to store multiple items in a single variable.
content.html: Sets are used to store multiple items in a single variable.

content.text: Set is one of 4 built-in data types in Python used to store collections of data, the other 3 are List , Tuple , and Dictionary , all with different qualities and usage.
content.html: Set is one of 4 built-in data types in Python used to store collections of data, the other 3 are List, Tuple, and Dictionary, all with different qualities and usage.

content.text: A set is a collection which is unordered , unchangeable* , and unindexed .
content.html: A set is a collection which is unordered, unchangeable*, and unindexed.

content.text: * Note: Set items are unchangeable, but you can remove items and add new items.
content.html: * Note: Set items are unchangeable, but you can remove items and add new items.

content.text: Sets are written with curly brackets.
content.html: Sets are written with curly brackets.

content.code_html:
thisset = {"apple", "banana", "cherry"}
print(thisset)

content.text: Note: Sets are unordered, so you cannot be sure in which order the items will appear.
content.html: Note: Sets are unordered, so you cannot be sure in which order the items will appear.

content.text: Set Items
Set items are unordered, unchangeable, and do not allow duplicate values.
content.html: Set items are unordered, unchangeable, and do not allow duplicate values.

content.text: Unordered
Unordered means that the items in a set do not have a defined order.
content.html: Unordered means that the items in a set do not have a defined order.

content.text: Set items can appear in a different order every time you use them, and cannot be referred to by index or key.
content.html: Set items can appear in a different order every time you use them, and cannot be referred to by index or key.

content.text: Unchangeable
Set items are unchangeable, meaning that we cannot change the items after the set has been created.
content.html: Set items are unchangeable, meaning that we cannot change the items after the set has been created.

content.text: Once a set is created, you cannot change its items, but you can remove items and add new items.
content.html: Once a set is created, you cannot change its items, but you can remove items and add new items.

content.text: Duplicates Not Allowed
Sets cannot have two items with the same value.
content.html: Sets cannot have two items with the same value.

content.code_html:
thisset = {"apple", "banana", "cherry", "apple"}

print(thisset)

content.text: Note: The values True and 1 are considered the same value in sets, and are treated as duplicates:
content.html: Note: The values True and 1 are considered the same value in sets, and are treated as duplicates:

content.code_html:
thisset = {"apple", "banana", "cherry", True, 1, 2}

print(thisset)

content.text: Note: The values False and 0 are considered the same value in sets, and are treated as duplicates:
content.html: Note: The values False and 0 are considered the same value in sets, and are treated as duplicates:

content.code_html:
thisset = {"apple", "banana", "cherry", False, True, 0}

print(thisset)

content.text: Get the Length of a Set
To determine how many items a set has, use the len() function.
content.html: To determine how many items a set has, use the len() function.

content.code_html:
thisset = {"apple", "banana", "cherry"}

print(len(thisset))

content.text: Set Items - Data Types
Set items can be of any data type:
content.html: Set items can be of any data type:

content.code_html:
set1 = {"apple", "banana", "cherry"}
set2 = {1, 5, 7, 9, 3}
set3 = {True, False, False}

content.text: A set can contain different data types:
content.html: A set can contain different data types:

content.code_html: set1 = {"abc", 34, True, 40, "male"}

content.text: type()
From Python's perspective, sets are defined as objects with the data type 'set':
content.html: From Python's perspective, sets are defined as objects with the data type 'set':

content.code_html:
myset = {"apple", "banana", "cherry"}
print(type(myset))

content.text: The set() Constructor
It is also possible to use the set() constructor to make a set.
content.html: It is also possible to use the set() constructor to make a set.
